                                         JOHANNESBURG - Chief editor of NPR’s newsroom Michael Oreskes has stepped down following allegations of sexual harassment dating back to the 90s. Two women had accused Oreskes of suddenly kissing them when they were discussing job prospects with him when he was Washington bureau chief of the New York Times. In a statement on Wednesday evening, he said his behaviour was wrong and he accepts responsibility. NPR CEO Jarl Mohn says he asked Michael Oreskes to resign “because of inappropriate behavior” pic.twitter.com/uRwiPq3QMi 